## Final Checklist

Before recording your video, verify:

### Azure Resources
- [ ] Resource group `MST300-project2-rg` created
- [ ] MST300-vnet1 created with `vnet1-subnet1` and `AzureBastionSubnet`
- [ ] MST300-vnet2 created with `vnet2-subnet1`
- [ ] No overlapping address spaces between VNets
- [ ] Azure Bastion deployed and running in AzureBastionSubnet
- [ ] No public IPs on any VM (only Bastion has a public IP)

### Load Balancer
- [ ] MST300-lb created as Internal type
- [ ] MST300-BackendPool configured with both webservers
- [ ] MST300-HealthProbe configured (HTTP, port 80, interval 15)
- [ ] MST300-HTTPRule configured (TCP, port 80, idle timeout 15)

### Web Servers
- [ ] webserver1-vm in Availability Zone 1
- [ ] webserver2-vm in Availability Zone 2
- [ ] IIS installed on both servers
- [ ] webserver1-vm: green background, correct title and body text
- [ ] webserver2-vm: yellow background, correct title and body text
- [ ] Both VMs tested locally with `http://localhost`

### Client VM
- [ ] client-vm running in MST300-vnet2 / vnet2-subnet1
- [ ] No public IP on client-vm

### Networking
- [ ] VNet peering between vnet1 and vnet2 — status **"Connected"**
- [ ] Peering configured in both directions

### Private DNS
- [ ] DNS zone named `studentID.mst300.com`
- [ ] Zone linked to both MST300-vnet1 and MST300-vnet2
- [ ] A record `www` pointing to load balancer frontend IP

### Testing
- [ ] Connected to client-vm via Bastion successfully
- [ ] Website loads at `http://www.studentID.mst300.com`
- [ ] Page alternates between green and yellow on refresh (InPrivate window)
- [ ] DNS resolves correctly via `nslookup`
